In the Strings.repeat method checks are performed to ensure that the resulting char[] array is not to large. In JDK9 or greater compact string are enabled by default so this check may produce a large char array which is less than Integer.MAX_VALUE but may result in a OutOfMemoryError if the string being repeated contains a single value that is not LATIN-1.

I'm not sure that this is a bug as such, only that the checks are performed
and it may be possible to prevent the array creation in the first place. For example, it may be possible to check that the repeat string has only LATIN-1 and then proceed as is; if not use a length value that is larger:

        int a = s.length();
        int b = s.codePointCount(0, s.length());
        int len = (a <= b) ? a : b*2;

I had a problem where I had some code like this:
```
    Duration oneWeek = Duration.ofDays(7);
    Duration oneMonth = Duration.ofDays(28);
    return oneWeek.compareTo(oneMonth) < 0;
```

The issue is only those that know how ```compareTo``` works realise it returns ```true```.

So I suggest adding some static methods like (e.g. in a class called ```Comparables```) to make it more readable:
```
  public static <C extends Comparable<? super C>> boolean isLessThan(C left, C right) {
    return left.compareTo(right) < 0;
  }
```

So the above can be expressed as:
```
    Duration oneWeek = Duration.ofDays(7);
    Duration oneMonth = Duration.ofDays(28);
    return isLessThan(oneWeek, oneMonth);
```

Would have other methods like ```isLessThanOrEqual```, ```isGreaterThan```, ```isGreaterThanOrEqual```

---

Or maybe, a class that wraps a ```Comparable``` (similar idea to ```Equivalence.Wrapper```) so it can be expressed like: 
```
    Wrapper<Duration> oneWeek = Wrapper.wrap(Duration.ofDays(7));
    Wrapper<Duration> oneMonth = Wrapper.wrap(Duration.ofDays(28));
    return oneWeek.isLessThan(oneMonth);
```

E.g. ```Wrapper``` looks like:
```
  public static class Wrapper<C extends Comparable<? super C>> {
    private final C object;

    public static <C extends Comparable<? super C>> Wrapper<C> wrap(C object) {
      return new Wrapper<>(object);
    }

    private Wrapper(C object) {
      this.object = requireNonNull(object);
    }

    public boolean isLessThan(Wrapper<? extends C> other) {
      return object.compareTo(other.object) < 0;
    }
  }
```

